Setting up: Install the following packages if you dont have them already

install.packages(c("igraph","ggplot2","rgdal","rgeos","geosphere"))

You only need to install these once, the next time that you will open R, the packages will be installed and you just need to call them as follows:

library(igraph)
library(rgdal)
library(rgeos)
library(ggplot2)
library(geosphere)

Extracting a map from OSM

There is a very good package available in Python that you can use instead to extract the road networks using the procedure defined below. The package is called osmx and was developed by Geoff Boeing: https://github.com/gboeing.

If you do not use python, you could still do it in R as follows. First extract the street networks from the following website: http://extract.bbbike.org. Since maps can come in many different formats, you need to be careful in extracting it in the right format. This needs to be Shapefile (Esri). After selecting the region of interest, you need to wait 5-7mins before receiving the file via email. To speed things up, I have extracted the road network for you for this session, it is inside the directory Central_London_Shapefile.

Let us read the shapefile downloaded from OSM:

folderSpatialData="Central_London_Shapefile/shape/"
shapeFile <- readOGR(dsn = folderSpatialData, "roads")

If we want the distance between the points, that is, in order to compute the length of the street, we need to either project the points which are in lat long or we need to compute the distance in the ellipsoid. Let us do the latter using a function constructed for this: distGeo

p1=data.frame(segments$x1,segments$y1)
p2=data.frame(segments$x2,segments$y2)
head(p2)
##   segments.x2 segments.y2

## 5    -0.11502    51.51874
## 6    -0.11502    51.52283
distance=distGeo(p1,p2)

Let us assign a new field to the segments: the distance

segments=data.frame(segments,distance=distance)

Although there are disconnected bits, ~96% of the nodes belong to the largest component.

Some disconnected components are the outcome of the way we selected the area of interest, while some others might be a problem in the construction of the road networks: segments of streets disconnected, etc.

Let us take only the largest connected component

gclust<-components(G_all, mode='weak')
largestConnectedComponent<-induced.subgraph(G_all, V(G_all)[which(gclust$membership == which.max(gclust$csize))])
G=largestConnectedComponent
all_weights=(E(G)$weight)
size_net=length(V(G))

And if we plot it again

plot(G,vertex.label=NA,vertex.size=.01)

Centrality measures

Let us now compute a centrality measure on this network. Let us use for example closeness centrality

closeness_G=closeness.estimate(G,cutoff=1000)
## Warning in closeness.estimate(G, cutoff = 1000): At centrality.c:
## 2617 :closeness centrality is not well-defined for disconnected graphs

Note that we use closeness.estimate instead of closeness. In the documentation igraph.org: estimate_closeness only considers paths of length cutoff or smaller, this can be run for larger graphs, as the running time is not quadratic (if cutoff is small). If cutoff is zero or negative then the function calculates the exact closeness scores.

Let us define some nice colours for our nodes in the map

getHSVColors=function(values,s=1,v=1){
  values=(values[values!=-1])
  vnorm=(values-min(values))/(max(values)-min(values))
  h=-2/3*vnorm+2/3
  colors=values
  colors[values!=-1]= hsv(h,s,v)
  colors[values==-1]= hsv(0,0,1)
  return (colors)
}

And let us plot it now

plot(G,vertex.size=2,vertex.color=getHSVColors(closeness_G),vertex.label=NA)

And what about the degree distribution???

degree_G=degree(G)
head(degree_G)
## 6226 6195 2758 2759 1292 2500 
##    2    3    1    2    2    2

Observe that most nodes have degree 2, as expected from this dataset. These biases need to be considered when transforming a dataset into a network. These artifical nodes do not represent the real morpholgy of the space.

Cleaning the network

This code was created by Mateo Neira, MSc student at CASA 2016-2017.

Let us create small area to clean graph since this code is very lenghtly to run

create bounding box (West, North, East, South)

delta_x=0.01
delta_y=0.008
T_West=min(V(G)$x)+delta_x
T_North= max(V(G)$y)-delta_y
T_East=max(V(G)$x)-delta_x
T_South=min(V(G)$y)+delta_y

bb_box<-c(T_West, T_North, T_East, T_South)

subset graph based on coordinates

nodes_to_remove<-V(G)[which((V(G)$x < bb_box[1] | V(G)$x > bb_box[3]) | (V(G)$y > bb_box[2] | V(G)$y < bb_box[4]))]$name
g_s<-delete.vertices(G, nodes_to_remove)

This must have generated several disconnected components

components(g_s)$no
## [1] 5

get largest connected component

gclust<-components(g_s, mode='weak')
largestConnectedComponent<-induced.subgraph(g_s, V(g_s)[which(gclust$membership == which.max(gclust$csize))])
G_s=largestConnectedComponent
plot(G_s,vertex.label=NA,vertex.size=.01)

get degree distribution of vertex

V(G_s)$deg<-degree(G_s)
deg<-as.data.frame(cbind(V(G_s)$name,V(G_s)$deg))
deg2<-as.character(deg[which(deg$V2==2),1])

create for loop to remove degree 2 nodes and reconnect edges

g_clean<-G_s
for(vrtx in c(1:length(deg2))){
  #print(deg2[vrtx])
  #get edge list to find which vertex degree two connect
  edge_list<-data.frame(cbind(get.edgelist(g_clean),E(g_clean)$weight))
  edge_list_2<-edge_list[which(edge_list$X1 %in% deg2[vrtx]),]
  edge_list_3<-edge_list[which(edge_list$X2 %in% deg2[vrtx]),]
  edge_list_3[,c("X1","X2")]<-edge_list_3[,c("X2","X1")]
  edge_list_2<-rbind(edge_list_2, edge_list_3)
  
  #add distances
  distance_list<-cbind(V=deg2[vrtx],D=sum(as.numeric(as.character(edge_list_2[,3]))))
  
  #edges
  edg<-c(as.character(edge_list_2[1,2]),as.character(edge_list_2[2,2]))
  
  #remove vertex
  g_clean<-delete.vertices(g_clean,deg2[vrtx])
  
  #add edges and distance
  g_clean<-add.edges(g_clean, edg, weight=sum(as.numeric(as.character(edge_list_2[,3]))))
}

Now let us compute a closeness centrality and plot the network

closeness_g_clean=closeness.estimate(g_clean,cutoff=1000)
## Warning in closeness.estimate(g_clean, cutoff = 1000): At centrality.c:
## 2617 :closeness centrality is not well-defined for disconnected graphs
plot(G_s, vertex.shape = 'none', vertex.label=NA, vertex.size = 1)
plot(g_clean,vertex.size=2,vertex.color=getHSVColors(closeness_g_clean),vertex.label=NA, add=TRUE, edge.color = NA)

Note that we cheated in the plot, in the sense that when removing nodes of degree 2 we also removed the streets that form elbows. In order to have then the right morphology, you will see that we plotted the network before cleaning without the vertices G_s, and then we put on top the vertices of the clean one g_clean.

Let us now look at the degree and verify that the cleaning took place as expected

degree_g_clean=degree(g_clean)
head(degree_g_clean)
## 1607 5914 7124 1658 7125 1629 
##    1    1    3    3    4    3
freq_degree=table(degree_g_clean)
plot(freq_degree)

As expected, all the nodes of degree 2 have been removed.
